<Link id="l00654" /><CodeLine lineNumber="654"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Attempt to claim responsibility for new definitions. This method can be</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00875" /><CodeLine lineNumber="875"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00876" /><CodeLine lineNumber="876"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// Represents a JIT&#39;d dynamic library.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00877" /><CodeLine lineNumber="877"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00878" /><CodeLine lineNumber="878"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// This class aims to mimic the behavior of a regular dylib or shared object,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00879" /><CodeLine lineNumber="879"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// but without requiring the contained program representations to be compiled</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00880" /><CodeLine lineNumber="880"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// up-front. The JITDylib&#39;s content is defined by adding MaterializationUnits,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00881" /><CodeLine lineNumber="881"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// and contained MaterializationUnits will typically rely on the JITDylib&#39;s</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00882" /><CodeLine lineNumber="882"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// links-against order to resolve external references (similar to a regular</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00883" /><CodeLine lineNumber="883"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// dylib).</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00884" /><CodeLine lineNumber="884"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00885" /><CodeLine lineNumber="885"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// The JITDylib object is a thin wrapper that references state held by the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00886" /><CodeLine lineNumber="886"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// ExecutionSession. JITDylibs can be removed, clearing this underlying state</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00887" /><CodeLine lineNumber="887"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// and leaving the JITDylib object in a defunct state. In this state the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00888" /><CodeLine lineNumber="888"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// JITDylib&#39;s name is guaranteed to remain accessible. If the ExecutionSession</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00889" /><CodeLine lineNumber="889"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// is still alive then other operations are callable but will return an Error</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00890" /><CodeLine lineNumber="890"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// or null result (depending on the API). It is illegal to call any operation</span></CodeLine>
